          "body": "Having stated His thesis (6:6), God marshals evidence in 6:7-10. The evidence comes in four movements. First, the Adamic comparison (6:7): 'Like Adam they have transgressed the covenant.' Whether Adam here is the man of Genesis 3 or a place name is debated among orthodox scholars; the canonical weight favors the man — Israel's covenant-breaking is as foundational and archetypal as humanity's first betrayal in the garden. Peter Davids and Douglas Moo, writing on the Pauline parallel in Romans 5, note that covenant transgression always carries this Adamic shape: the creature given a beautiful provision responds with betrayal. Second, Gilead (6:8): a territory of political murders, its ground tracked with blood. Third, the priests (6:9): the men charged with guiding Israel to the knowledge of God instead ambush and murder on the road to Shechem, the city of covenant and refuge. This is Hosea's sharpest priestly indictment since 4:4-10 — the shepherds are wolves. Fourth, Ephraim (6:10): harlotry (*zenut*) and defilement (*tame*) — the cultic apostasy of Baal-worship has contaminated the entire national covenant identity. The four movements together show that the covenant failure is total: it reaches from the archetypal past (Adam) to the national present (Ephraim), from civic leadership (Gilead) to religious leadership (priests)."
