          "title": "Judah included, restoration announced (6:11)",
          "body": "The chapter closes with a single verse of double register. 'Also, O Judah, there is a harvest appointed for you' — the southern kingdom, which throughout Hosea has served as an implicit contrast to the more flagrant north, is now explicitly included in the indictment. The harvest (*qatsir*) appointed for Judah is judicial; the same image is used in Joel 3:13, Jeremiah 51:33, and Revelation 14:15 for the divine reaping of judgment. But the verse does not end there. The second half pivots: 'when I restore the fortunes of My people.' The phrase *shevut shiv* (restore the fortunes) is a technical expression for the end of exile and the reversal of covenant curse — it appears across the prophetic corpus (Jeremiah 30:3, 18; 33:7; Amos 9:14; Zephaniah 3:20; Joel 3:1) as the definitive eschatological hope. Judgment and restoration are not sequential alternatives; they are simultaneous vectors in God's single covenant purpose. The same harvest that reaps judgment plants restoration. The chapter that opens with a call to return (6:1) closes with God's commitment to the return He will one day make possible on His own terms — not the superficial return of 6:1-3, but the deep restoration of a people whose fortunes God Himself has reversed."
