        "excerpt": "Come, let us return to the LORD. For He has torn us, but He will heal us… What shall I do with you, O Ephraim?",
        "body": "The juxtaposition of 6:1-3 and 6:4 is Hosea's sharpest rhetorical move in the chapter. Israel's words in 6:1-3 are not obviously wrong — they are theologically orthodox. God does heal. He does revive. His coming is dawn-certain and rain-generous. The problem is what the words do not say. The call to return contains no named sin, no specific acknowledgment of the covenant violations catalogued in chapters 4-5 (the priestly failure of 4:4-10, the harlotry of 4:11-19, the political treachery of 5:1-15). It is a return to the idea of God's restorative power, not a return from the specific paths that provoked His discipline.\n\nThe 'two days / third day' of 6:2 has generated extensive commentary. In its immediate literary context, the phrase functions as a Hebraic idiom of brevity — 'after a short time He will restore us' — expressing Israel's confidence that the discipline will be swift and the healing swifter. The canonical question of whether 6:2 anticipates the resurrection of Christ is legitimate and debated among orthodox scholars. Those who see a direct Messianic prediction point to Paul's citation of 'raised on the third day according to the Scriptures' (1 Corinthians 15:4) without specifying which scriptures, and to the early church's use of Hosea in resurrection apologetics (Irenaeus, Tertullian). Those who prefer a typological reading (John Calvin, most Reformed exegetes) argue that 6:2 speaks primarily of national restoration and that its fulfillment in the resurrection of Christ is a fuller meaning the text bears without exhausting its first-order referent. Both positions are within the bounds of orthodox interpretation; neither should be held with excessive dogmatic certainty.\n\nGod's counter-question in 6:4 — 'What shall I do with you?' — is not rhetorical despair but diagnostic interrogation. The double address (Ephraim, Judah) refuses to let either kingdom hide behind the other's greater guilt. The similes of morning mist and early dew are precisely calibrated: both are associated in Hosea with apparent blessing (dew returns in the restoration promise of 14:5 — 'I will be like the dew to Israel'), and both disappear under the sun's heat. Israel's chesed is real at the moment of cultic enthusiasm and gone before the day's competing allegiances arrive.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Shub* (return/repent) in 6:1 is the standard prophetic word for covenant repentance — used 1,059 times in the Hebrew Bible. Its presence here without accompanying moral specificity is itself the diagnostic clue. *Yom hashelishi* (third day, 6:2) — Hebrew idiom for a brief but decisive interval (cf. Genesis 22:4; Exodus 19:11; Jonah 1:17); its Christological resonance in 1 Corinthians 15:4 has led exegetes from Origen to Keil to revisit its depth."
