        "title": "The evidence — covenant-breaking from Adam to Ephraim",
        "range": "6:7-10",
        "excerpt": "But like Adam they have transgressed the covenant; there they have dealt treacherously against Me.",
        "body": "Having stated His thesis (6:6), Yahweh assembles evidence in 6:7-10. The evidence is not incidental — it is structured to show that the covenant failure is total, reaching across history (Adam), geography (Gilead), the religious establishment (priests/Shechem), and the national identity (Ephraim/Israel).\n\nThe Adam comparison (6:7) is the chapter's most contested exegetical question. Three readings are possible within orthodox scholarship: (a) 'like Adam' refers to the man of Genesis 3 — Israel's covenant-breaking recapitulates humanity's first act of covenant betrayal in the garden; (b) 'like Adam' refers to the city of Adam (Tell ed-Damiyeh, near the Jordan), making it a geographic parallel to Gilead and Shechem in the following verses; (c) 'like men' (reading 'adam as the generic noun) following the LXX tradition. The canonical argument for reading (a) is strong: the pairing of *avar berit* (transgressed the covenant) with *bagad* (dealt treacherously) in a single verse most naturally evokes the garden narrative, and the Pauline covenant-Adam typology of Romans 5 suggests the early church read Hosea in this Adamic frame. Calvin favored reading (a) and found in it the deepest possible indictment: Israel is not merely behaving badly — they are recapitulating the foundational human sin of covenant betrayal.\n\nGilead (6:8) is tracked with blood — the language of violence, murder, and political conspiracy. In the period Hosea prophesied (750s-720s BC), the northern kingdom experienced four violent regicides in twenty years (2 Kings 15:8-30). Gilead, home of several northern military figures, is named as a synecdoche for the systemic political bloodshed that had replaced covenant governance.\n\nThe priests of 6:9 represent the chapter's most devastating reversal. The men charged by the Mosaic covenant to teach da'at elohim (4:6), to guard the sanctuary, and to guide the people in holiness are instead compared to bandits lying in ambush. The road to Shechem was a pilgrimage route to a city of refuge — the most protected person in Israelite law was the manslayer on his way to a city of refuge (Numbers 35:25-28). The priests murder precisely that person, on precisely that road. The covenant's most sacred protection has been turned into a hunting ground by its appointed protectors.\n\nEphraim's harlotry (6:10) closes the catalogue with the book's ruling metaphor: zenut, the prostitution of spiritual unfaithfulness. Israel has not merely made ethical mistakes; she has betrayed her husband (the metaphor established in chapters 1-3). The defilement (*tame*) is not incidental — it is the Levitical language of ritual uncleanness that disqualifies from the sanctuary's presence. Israel has made herself unfit for the very worship she is performing."
